---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Beat from '../components/Beat.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import BrandIcon from '../components/BrandIcon.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="How Ikenga works — cockpit and package manager for Claude Code"
	description="Your Claude Code setup is powerful, but it lives in scattered dotfiles. Ikenga is the cockpit and package manager that gives it a home — one screen, on your machine."
	canonical="https://ikenga.dev/how-it-works"
>

	<!-- Hero -->
	<section class="sk-hero sk-section--flush">
		<div class="sk-wrap">
			<p class="sk-eyebrow">How it works</p>
			<h1 class="sk-display">How <em>Ikenga</em> works</h1>
			<p class="sk-lede">
				Your Claude Code setup is powerful, but it lives in scattered dotfiles: agents in
				<code>~/.claude/agents/</code>, skills in <code>~/.claude/skills/</code>, MCP servers in a
				JSON config you hand-edit every time. Ikenga is the cockpit and package manager that gives
				it a home — one screen, on your machine.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Section: One screen for your whole Claude setup (Beat with ngwa-cockpit image) -->
	<Beat
		heading="One screen for your whole Claude setup"
		img="/assets/shell/ngwa-cockpit.png"
		alt="The Ikenga cockpit showing agents, skills, commands, hooks, and MCP servers across projects"
		caption="The cockpit — all your Claude config visible at once"
		eager={true}
	>
		<p class="sk-body">
			The cockpit is a visual surface that shows every agent, skill, command, hook, and MCP server
			across all your projects and scopes. Enable or disable any of them without opening a file. See
			what's installed, what's active, and where each piece lives — across every project at once,
			without switching terminals or editors.
		</p>
	</Beat>

	<!-- Section: A package manager, not a dotfile editor (Beat with oba-store image, reversed) -->
	<Beat
		heading="A package manager, not a dotfile editor"
		img="/assets/shell/oba-store.png"
		alt="The Ikenga package manager showing installed packages with provenance and update controls"
		caption="The package manager — install, update, and remove with full provenance"
		reverse={true}
	>
		<p class="sk-body">
			The package manager installs and updates agents, skills, commands, and pkgs from git or npx —
			with provenance, dependent-aware safe-uninstall, and an auto-update option. A catalog lets you
			discover what the community has built. You manage your Claude config the same way you manage
			your dependencies: with a tool that knows what's installed, where it came from, and how to
			remove it cleanly.
		</p>
	</Beat>

	<!-- Section: The engine is swappable (copy-only — no matching image) -->
	<section class="sk-section">
		<div class="sk-wrap">
			<h2 class="sk-h2">The engine is swappable</h2>
			<p class="sk-body">
				The reasoning core — your Chi — is a pluggable adapter.
				<BrandIcon name="claude" /> Claude Code is fully wired today;
				<BrandIcon name="codex" /> Codex and <BrandIcon name="gemini" /> Gemini plug into the
				same slot. Switch the engine without rebuilding your workspace, because the engine
				ships as a package, separate from the shell.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Section: Everything is a package (copy-only) -->
	<section class="sk-section">
		<div class="sk-wrap">
			<h2 class="sk-h2">Everything is a package</h2>
			<p class="sk-body">
				Beyond the cockpit and package manager, everything in the workspace extends via independently
				installable packages: mini-apps, tool servers (including MCP bridges), engine adapters, and
				bundled command-line tools. Packages install, update, and retire when you're done with them.
				Two small command-line tools sit underneath: <code>ikenga</code> manages packages on disk,
				and <code>iyke</code> drives a running workspace.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Section: Local-first by default (copy-only) -->
	<section class="sk-section">
		<div class="sk-wrap">
			<h2 class="sk-h2">Local-first by default</h2>
			<p class="sk-body">
				Ikenga runs on your machine. Your config, your files, and your agents' data stay where you
				put them — in local SQLite and files, not a cloud service. There's no account to create and
				nothing to upload to use it. When you want hosting or a managed setup, that's a choice you
				make — not a default you have to opt out of.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Foot CTA -->
	<section class="sk-section">
		<div class="sk-wrap sk-obi">
			<h2 class="sk-h2">See it for yourself</h2>
			<div class="sk-obi__cta">
				<Button href="/docs/getting-started" variant="primary">
					Read the getting-started guide
				</Button>
				<Button href="/packages" variant="ghost">
					Browse the packages
				</Button>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

</Layout>
